snippet.textDisplay: SARS coronavirus (SARS-CoV) – virus identified in 2003. SARS-CoV is thought to be an animal virus from an as-yet-uncertain animal reservoir, perhaps bats, that spread to other animals (civet cats) and first infected humans in the Guangdong province of southern China in 2002, An epidemic of SARS affected 26 countries and resulted in more than 8000 cases in 2003. Since then, a small number of cases have occurred as a result of laboratory accidents or, possibly, through animal-to-human transmission (Guangdong, China).

snippet.textDisplay:
On a side note, I think "COVID-19" is a terrible name for the new disease. Disease names have to be descriptive and unique. There's nothing as particular about "coronavirus disease 2019" compared to SARS and MERS. It's a shame, really.
My humble suggestions are CIP (coronavirus induced pneumopathy)
CLRS (coronaviral lower respiratory syndrome)
Or...what the heck....MARS (moderate acute respiratory syndrome)

snippet.textDisplay:
There are 4 main sub-groupings of coronaviruses: alpha, beta, gamma, and delta

Common human coronavirus
1) 229E (alpha coronavirus)
2) NL63 (alpha as well)
3) OC43 (beta)
4) HKU1 (beta)

5) MERS CoV (beta)
6) SARS CoV (beta)
7) SARS CoV-2 (the new coronavirus)

Some coronavirus that infect animals can undergo a certain mutation and developed into a new coronavirus.

Source: cdc.gov
